{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01U3demnisJstCU25aUiDub2","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The nginx config shows:\n1. `limit_req_status 429;` - returning 429 for rate-limited requests ✓\n2. `limit_req_zone ... rate=1r/s;` - 1 request per second zone ✓\n3. `limit_req zone=... burst=5 nodelay;` - applying rate limiting with burst=5 nodelay\n\nWait - the problem is `burst=5 nodelay`. With a burst of 5 and nodelay, the first 5 requests above the 1 QPS limit will be immediately served (burst=5 allows 5 requests to be queued/served immediately), and subsequent requests beyond the burst+rate will be limited.\nSo in the test with 10 requests at 2 QPS, the first 6 requests should pass through (1 baseline + 5 burst), and the remaining 4 should get rejected with 429. we're sending 10 requests at 2 QPS (every 0.5 seconds), which means most will fall within the burst allowance of 5, so the test isn't actually hitting the rate limit as intended. The burst window is too generous for this request pattern. I see the real issue now—with a burst of 5 and a rate of 1 request per second, the burst can absorb the excess traffic from our 2 QPS test for about 5 seconds, which is why most requests are passing. I need to reduce the burst size using the `limit-burst-multiplier` annotation to make the rate limiting actually kick in during the test. So with `nodelay`, burst tokens get consumed immediately without adding delay, which means requests 1-6 would pass right away, but then requests 7-10 should hit the limit once the burst is exhausted. The fact that we're seeing zero rejections suggests the burst might not be configured correctly or the rate limiting isn't being applied as expected. Continuing through the timeline, requests 6 through 10 all pass as the excess bucket stays below the burst limit of 5, so all ten requests would be allowed through with the given rate and burst configuration.\n\nNow I'm realizing that reducing the burst multiplier to 1 would be the fix, but I need to understand whether the burst parameter is inclusive or exclusive of the rate limit to determine the exact behavior at the boundary. Looking at the nginx source code formula for how excess requests are calculated relative to the burst window... I'm going to simplify this and just test with a burst multiplier of 2 to see how the rate limiting actually behaves. With burst=2 and rate=1r/s, the token bucket will be consumed faster than it's replenished, so after about 2 seconds the burst capacity is exhausted and subsequent requests start getting rejected.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":783,"cache_read_input_tokens":37751,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":783},"output_tokens":31,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2141b0f2-7bdb-4cbb-9fdc-5be2d7630d9b","uuid":"e1a588d5-0c8e-4097-b546-aab983cecb07","request_id":"req_011Cc4AWbDd2uycRBajKWBtU"}
